# Branch And PR Safety

- Never commit or push directly to `main` or `develop`.
- Before making repo changes, check the current branch. If it is `main` or `develop`, create a feature or fix branch first.
- Feature branches normally target `develop`; target `main` only for an explicitly requested stable baseline promotion or emergency fix.
- Prefer small reviewable PRs. Split unrelated work instead of bundling it into one broad branch.
- When the user asks for commits, make each commit atomic: one coherent purpose, one reviewable behavior or documentation change, and no unrelated cleanup.
- Stage deliberately. Do not sweep all changed files into a commit unless every staged change belongs to the same atomic purpose.
- Keep each commit immediately understandable from its diff and its message. A human reviewer should be able to review the commit without reverse-engineering the whole branch.
- Use Conventional Commit-style messages for every commit: `<type>(<scope>): <summary>`. Choose the type that matches the purpose, such as `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `test`, `refactor`, `chore`, or `ci`.
- Write commit summaries in the imperative mood and explain the "why" in the body when the reason is not obvious from the diff.
- Do not run destructive git commands such as `git reset --hard`, `git checkout -- <path>`, force pushes, or branch deletion unless the user explicitly approves that exact action.
- Do not revert user changes unless the user explicitly asks. If existing changes overlap with the task, work with them and call out any conflict.
- When responding to PR comments, only claim a fix exists after making a real commit. Include the commit link when replying that something was fixed.
